There's no need for a loose translation - the word has a specific one which, like the English counterpart, can be used vaguely in a lay context or specifically in a specialised one. The same distinction between "tactics" and "strategy" is observed in Japanese as in English, and 戦術 corresponds to the former, as both monolingual (Daijirin) and bilingual (Jisho, Cambridge, Weblio) dictionaries will bear out, as will a Google search of "戦術と戦略" - "tactics and strategy"
